INSERT INTO `wp_unrgrx_comments` VALUES (10,5,'assnose','assnose@likit.kljs','http://potliker','66.191.16.55','2003-07-12 09:49:46','2003-07-12 16:49:46','sgytbvchaflrgykhbvsrf\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(11,5,'Lonnon','lonnon.foster@gmail.com','http://blog.nyerm.com','12.231.122.27','2003-07-13 09:49:01','2003-07-13 16:49:01','This is the kind of insightful, well-written comment that makes having a blog worthwhile. Thank you, \"assnose\".\r\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(959,11,'Lonnon','lonnon.foster@gmail.com','http://blog.nyerm.com','131.107.3.92','2003-11-13 09:48:44','2003-11-13 16:48:44','I\'d never heard of El Rey before, but their Web site\r\n(<a href=\"http://www.chocolates-elrey.com/)\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.chocolates-elrey.com/)</a> looks pretty good. Thanks for pointing them out to me. I can never have enough chocolate.\r\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(960,11,'Chuck','aacharliew@netscape.net','http://www.worldwidechocolates.com','192.223.226.5','2005-02-11 08:00:46','2005-02-11 15:00:46','www.worldwidechocolates.com seems to be a pretty good place for buying chocolates the \"e\" way...great selection, whimsical website, and good service...oh, and the best chocolate\'s anywhere\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(962,11,'Belgian Chocolate Online','chocolat@ucwphilly.rr.com','http://www.chocolat.com','68.174.73.36','2005-04-29 06:01:04','2005-04-29 13:01:04','Belgian Chocolate Online\nIf you love chocolate, it is a MUST to visit Belgian Chocolate Online, the largest online chocolate store. There is simply no better place to find quality chocolate from Europe and South America.\n\nIf you don\'t like chocolate, you will learn to love it and to treat yourself acquiring a taste for it, which you could do by ordering a ton of the best chocolates from Belgian Chocolate Online. With enough operant conditioning, you\'ll be enjoying melt-in-your-mouth goodness in no time.\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(964,11,'henry','h_mylo@yahoo.com','','216.117.219.146','2006-03-30 14:29:00','2006-03-30 21:29:00','Swiss chocolate is better than Belgium and the best Swiss chocolate I have found here in the US has been Intemperantia chocolates.  I have ordered these online and I do it at least once a month. www.intemperantia.com\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(1421,13,'progster','','','213.224.83.102','2003-05-07 08:35:24','2003-05-07 15:35:24','won\'t whatever work as well? (actually I should test that... *lazy*)\n\n~Progster\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(1422,13,'Lonnon','lonnon.foster@gmail.com','http://blog.nyerm.com','207.46.228.16','2003-05-07 10:59:00','2003-05-07 17:59:00','The formatting that you\'re talking about, which got munched by Movable Type, is &lt;span title=\"Sealed With A Kiss\"&gt;SWAK&lt;/span&gt;. Yes, using span with a title does allow for a tool tip to appear when you hover the mouse over the text, but there\'s no visual indication of an acronym, so the user has no way of knowing that she can mouse over the word.\r\n\r\nMozilla and its descendents put a dotted underline under words with the &lt;acronym&gt; or &lt;abbr&gt; tags to let you know that you can hover to get an expanded definition via tool tip. IE displays a tool tip, but it unfortunately doesn\'t have any visual indicator that there\'s an acronym lurking there in the text.\r\n\r\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(1423,13,'meena','minu_meetme@yahoo.co.in','','202.88.237.24','2003-08-12 03:45:45','2003-08-12 10:45:45','hai\'\nhow can we format the text in the title of an acronyam\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(1424,13,'adyus','adyus@adyus.net','http://www.adyus.net','220.97.109.227','2003-08-13 21:40:56','2003-08-14 04:40:56','Just stumbled upon this page googling for acronym :)\nAren\'t blogs just great?\nProgster, can\'t you fix the \"nothing showing it\'s an acronym\" problem in Explorer by using CSS and underlining it?\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(1425,13,'Henrik Gemal','no@spam.com','http://gemal.dk/mt/','80.199.87.10','2003-10-29 07:38:17','2003-10-29 14:38:17','Why dont you use MT::Plugins::Acronym ?\n\nAcronym is a plugin for Movable Type that adds acronym tags to known acronyms.\n\nhttp://gemal.dk/mt/\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(1426,13,'Lonnon','lonnon.foster@gmail.com','http://blog.nyerm.com','12.229.112.144','2003-10-29 13:34:38','2003-10-29 20:34:38','I\'d never heard of MT::Plugins::Acronym. Thank you for pointing it out to me; I may have to install it and give it a whirl.\r\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(1427,13,'Dhiraj Gupta','dhiraj@dhirajgupta.com','http://dhiraj.wordpress.com','221.128.170.214','2006-02-04 09:10:37','2006-02-04 16:10:37','Can you assign a URL to the acronym as well? I mean, it looks like a much more convenient html tag than using the a href=\"whatever\" title=\"whatever\" routine.\n\nPerhaps a way to have the link on the tooltip, itself? Or am I asking too much? ;-)\n\nDhiraj.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(1428,13,'Lonnie','lonnief@pobox.com','http://tribblescape.com/','192.94.202.44','2006-02-06 11:16:33','2006-02-06 18:16:33','Well, throwing links and such into an acronym tag might be possible with Javascript, but honestly, it\'s an abuse of the semantics of the tag. The &lt;acronym&gt; tag should only be used for acronyms; the &lt;a&gt; tag is really what\'s intended for making links.\n\nUsing the wrong tag for the job causes more problems than offending the sensibilities of semantic markup wonks like me. Screen readers and other alternative browser types rely on the semantics of tags like &lt;acronym&gt; and &lt;a&gt; to be used as they were originally intended, and changing how you use these basic tags can cause a real mess for these browsers when they try to figure out how to render the page.\n\nNow, if you want to get all fancy about it while maintaining proper semantics, I suppose you could add scripting to an &lt;a&gt; tag that would pop up some kind of hovertext linky thing, but it\'s still a departure from how most people are used to using the Web, which makes it terrible from an accessibility standpoint. Convention is a good thing if you want your website to be usable.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(1429,13,'Tzaddi','zodzilla@gmail.com','http://zodomatica.com/log','70.71.45.209','2006-02-06 21:03:23','2006-02-07 04:03:23','I found your site googling \"acronym\", but now that  I see your \"Biological posting only\" I have to ask: is it an MT plugin or part of the newer MT? I use an old version of MT and the spammers still get me now and then. (I do use MT-blacklist but it\'s more reactive than this method.) Thanks.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(3632,24,'ip address','sahj2000@hotmail.com','http://www.ip2location.com','219.95.3.79','2003-05-04 00:31:43','2003-05-04 07:31:43','ok dokie\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(3633,24,'bhupinder','','','203.57.45.248','2005-03-01 04:07:21','2005-03-01 11:07:21','cool\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(4378,28,'pimpkin','elisna@gmail.com','','211.24.250.63','2005-12-31 21:57:30','2006-01-01 04:57:30','h\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(4379,28,'Rohdesign Weblog','','http://www.rohdesign.com/weblog/archives/000150.html','209.61.187.47','2003-08-13 11:44:48','2003-08-13 18:44:48','<strong>Good Thinking on Email</strong>\n\nLast week I came across an older post from March 11th over at Lonnie Foster\'s weblog, which I really liked and wanted to share here. Lonnie\'s post linked to and talked about an Ole Eichhorn essay called The Tyranny of...\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(6656,37,'Jwahar Bammi','bammi@memento-inc.com','','155.212.201.202','2005-04-06 14:20:48','2005-04-06 21:20:48','A recipe detailing how you did it will be much appreciated.\n\nthanks\n++jrb\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(6672,40,'Patrick','patrick@the-professionals.com','http://www.the-professionals.com','68.116.69.145','2003-07-22 02:19:18','2003-07-22 09:19:18','Hello! Glad you liked the skinner. I have a windows version now up on my website that has a lot more features and is much easier to use.\n\nPatrick\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(8454,47,'Res','resqdog51@hotmail.com','http://www.livejournal.com/users/resqdog51/','4.40.46.161','2003-04-03 10:23:05','2003-04-03 17:23:05','*laugh*\n\nIf anyone would get it, it would be you, dear...\n\n*laugh*  that is so typical of your experiences!\n\nRes\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(64409,185,'JOHN','CARDOC@NNEX.NET','','207.14.76.83','2008-04-10 05:20:38','2008-04-10 12:20:38','WHISPER CHIPPER MEANS THAT MOST IKELY THAT EVERYTHING THAT YOU HEAR AFTER USING THIS UNIT SOUNDS LIKE A WHISPER!  EAR PROTECTION IS A MUST !  OH! FOR ANYONE WITHIN A 100 YARDS TOO!\r\nI HAVE ONE OF THESE I BOUGHT JUST TO GET 40 ACRES OF PROPERTY CLEANED UP AFTER SELECT CUTTING WAS DONE. SOUNDS LIKE THE DISTANT NEIGHHBORS WILL BE CALLING ME.  DON\'T KNOW WHAT THO!!',0,'1','Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 7.0; Windows NT 5.1; .NET CLR 1.1.4322; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; .NET CLR 3.0.04506.30)','',0,0),(10656,66,'hswallow','hswallow@email.com','','81.86.161.174','2003-04-29 00:02:37','2003-04-29 07:02:37','In England, the phrase \"on a hiding to nothing\" means something different from what you have discovered.\n\nMy Oxford Dictionary gives the meaning as \"in a position from which there can be no successful outcome\", although it gives no clue as to the derivation.\n\nIn fact, it was said on the BBC news today that the US forces searching for WMD in Iraq are on a hiding to nothing.  In other words, if they don\'t find any, they will be criticised for going to war on a false premise, and if they do find them, they will be criticised for planting them in order to justify the war.\n\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(10657,66,'Peter','impleader@gmail.com','http://impleader.com','68.101.163.74','2005-02-19 17:37:38','2005-02-20 00:37:38','spiffy phrase.  i\'ll start using it now\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(10658,66,'Mike','','','24.67.253.203','2005-07-22 12:37:36','2005-07-22 19:37:36','I\'ve recently come across this phrase used in the book \"Odds and Gods\" by the British author Tom Holt.  It is an incredibly funny book, in the style of Douglas Adams, but applied to the Pantheon of gods.  Osiris is on a hiding to nothing against his godson Julian, who wants to declare Osiris insane and claim the family estate. The phrase is used frequently and has had me baffled throughout.  Finally, I decided to look the damn thing up.\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(10659,66,'Anne','anne@annerix.demon.co.uk','','158.152.163.215','2006-03-24 14:24:10','2006-03-24 21:24:10','I\'ve puzzled as to the origin of this phrase which (apart from the horseracing suggestion) is apparently meaningless.  It was the title of an episode of a TV programme in the late \'70s (which could of course have been a play on words) and I wondered if it could be a corruption of \'a siding to nowhere\' which is a reference to bits of railway track that branch off the main line but end shortly (rolling stock can be stored there out of the way, but don\'t go anywhere ...).   Somewhere I\'ve seen \'hiding to nowhere\' given as an alternative to \'hiding to nothing\', which would fit my hypothesis.  And one shade of meaning (working hard at something that isn\'t going to get you anywhere) seems to be equivalent to \'flogging a dead horse\' which links with the racing explanation ... fun, isn\'t it?\nAnne\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(10660,66,'tribe.net: tribble.dreamhost.com','','http://boston.tribe.net/thread/945770de-893f-4857-b4f3-1e360394991e?tribeid=54643264-050c-45b0-b5f1-03a496a1bc83&amp;r=10509#9d4cdc74-8ce2-4927-8570-12154307fa5b','209.81.40.66','2005-02-05 16:52:16','2005-02-05 23:52:16','<strong>on a hiding to nothing</strong>\n\njust came across this phrase while reading one of my favorite writers, domini...\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(10661,66,'tribe.net: tribble.dreamhost.com','','http://boston.tribe.net/thread/f11234dd-0552-4990-a514-04737a50101e?tribeid=9041b71f-8809-4ddf-adc8-d95bddd62133&amp;r=10509#e85085d8-c758-40c8-8e52-72cde05c0f56','209.81.40.66','2005-02-05 20:23:30','2005-02-06 03:23:30','<strong>Re: fashionable anti-americanism</strong>\n\nim glad you asked.\n--\nThe phrase dates to 1905 and is apparently from horse...\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(11890,73,'Dave Winer\'s Demo Site','','http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/crimson1/2003/04/25#a134','140.247.216.119','2003-04-25 10:10:49','2003-04-25 17:10:49','<strong>Testing Manila outbound trackback</strong>\n\nI\'m testing the new support for Trackback in Manila, in development.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(11891,73,'Dave Winer\'s Demo Site','','http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/crimson1/2003/04/25#a134','140.247.216.119','2003-04-25 10:12:38','2003-04-25 17:12:38','<strong>Testing Manila outbound trackback</strong>\n\nI\'m testing the new support for Trackback in Manila, in development.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(11892,73,'Dave Winer\'s Demo Site','','http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/crimson1/2003/04/25#a134','140.247.216.119','2003-04-25 10:15:51','2003-04-25 17:15:51','<strong>Testing Manila outbound trackback</strong>\n\nI\'m testing the new support for Trackback in Manila, in development.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(14439,92,'Adam Greenfield','adam@v-2.org','http://www.v-2.org','211.4.48.19','2003-05-02 07:45:25','2003-05-02 14:45:25','\'Twas me that posted it, Lonnie, and I\'d be happy to try and snag one for you from Tokyu Hands if we can figure out a payment/shipping plan that works for you.\n\nI\'d advise you to wait for my review/comparison test of the City 1.2.3 vs. the Boblbee Megalopolis, coming next week on v-2. A quick heads-up: straight from the box, as it were, the Isaburo bag is a backpack ONLY. The necessary straps to configure it as lumbar bag or shoulderbag are accessories-sold-separately.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(17785,124,'Taylor','','http://gtmcknight.com','4.63.229.65','2003-05-22 15:46:20','2003-05-22 22:46:20','All those links could\'ve been found on the \"Make One\" Page (http://gtmcknight.com/buttons/make.html) all along :D  But glad you found them and enjoy the buttons!\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(17786,124,'Lonnon','lonnon.foster@gmail.com','http://blog.nyerm.com','12.231.122.27','2003-05-23 09:49:26','2003-05-23 16:49:26','You mean, I should actually click those linky thingies at the top of your page? Damn. Why didn\'t I think of that? :)\r\n\r\nIf I had more time, my blog would already be littered with buttons from your page. Great resource, Taylor.\r\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(17982,132,'sujal','','http://www.fatmixx.com','192.233.92.200','2003-05-23 14:15:54','2003-05-23 21:15:54','\nIt\'s either tracking info or, more likely IMHO, just randomly added text that will aid in getting around mail and spam filters.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(17983,132,'Lonnon','lonnon.foster@gmail.com','http://blog.nyerm.com','12.231.122.27','2003-05-23 15:26:19','2003-05-23 22:26:19','Yeah, I\'d thought about the tracking info idea, though usually that takes the form of random gibberish on the subject line. I think you\'ve hit the nail on the head, though: what better text to include but Shakespeare if you\'re attempting to include \"real English\" that gets around spam filters?\r\n\r\nThis message did get around Bogofilter, by the way, which I\'ve had installed for a month and a half now. It\'s a truly stellar filter, relying on Bayesian statistical analysis to tell spam apart from real mail. I reclassified the message as spam, so there\'s a good chance that I won\'t see too many Shakespearean email messages in the future. It\'s kind of sad, in a way.\r\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(17986,134,'Michael Montoure','montoure@bloodletters.com','http://www.bloodletters.com/','216.231.35.138','2003-05-24 12:16:55','2003-05-24 19:16:55','Heh.  You\'re quite welcome.\n\nIt\'s really strange to me that you were pretty much the *only* person who ended up on the site because I know them in person; I would have thought that in our extended social circle of geeks, more of the people we know would have gravitated toward blogging, but it doesn\'t look like it.\n\nGlad you like the site -- I\'ve had a lot of fun putting it together, and I\'m really pleased with how it\'s turned out.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(18207,135,'Dina Cash','ptchic_05@yahoo.com','','68.37.64.250','2005-01-28 21:21:22','2005-01-29 04:21:22','starting a band need stickers.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(19299,145,'ofer','ljhh@gfcg.lk.iu','','212.25.123.17','2003-10-01 22:24:25','2003-10-02 05:24:25','i want something\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(19538,147,'Jane Jolin','Jane_Jolin@yahoo.com','http://www.celebrityblog.net','212.179.195.182','2005-08-05 07:35:11','2005-08-05 14:35:11','I\'m very excited about the project as I just finished a design theme for csszengarden.com\nYou can have a look at <a href=\"http://www.celebrityblog.net/zengarden/zengarden-sample.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">celebrity CSS Zen Garden theme design</a>\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(19539,148,'Tracy','tracyk@parc.com','http://www.parc.com','13.1.136.7','2003-07-08 10:40:51','2003-07-08 17:40:51','Please update your website. We are no longer called Xerox PARC.  We are now know as PARC.\n\nPlease see www.parc.com for modular robotics info at   http://www2.parc.com/spl/projects/modrobots/\n\nThanks.\n\nTracy K.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(19540,148,'Lonnon','lonnon.foster@gmail.com','http://blog.nyerm.com','12.231.122.27','2003-07-08 11:33:57','2003-07-08 18:33:57','My apologies; I\'ve known the labs in Palo Alto as \"Xerox PARC\" for so long, I hadn\'t realized that the name had officially changed. It\'s fixed in the article now.\r\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(64433,312,'Colleen','cmjay1213@yahoo.com','','208.73.108.66','2008-04-23 09:08:46','2008-04-23 16:08:46','Does anyone have the mid file for the Kimmunicator tone?  I\'ve looked everywhere!!  You can e-mail me at cmjay1213 AT yahoo DOT you know what.  Thanks!',0,'1','Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US; rv:1.8.0.12) Gecko/20070508 Firefox/1.5.0.12','',0,0),(64465,371,'lonnon','lonnon.foster@gmail.com','http://nyerm.com','192.94.202.91','2008-05-05 10:00:48','2008-05-05 17:00:48','Wow. Sit around in one place long enough on the net, and the world comes knocking. Hi, James! @\\o_@',0,'1','Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; Intel Mac OS X; en-US; rv:1.8.1.14) Gecko/20080404 Firefox/2.0.0.14','',0,2),(64464,371,'James','kd7spt@hotmail.com','','67.160.150.221','2008-05-05 05:02:52','2008-05-05 12:02:52','Yes, we got some solid precipitation down south here in Vancouver too (some hail and some snow).  Good to finally figure out that you are still kicking!  Drop me a line.\r\nJames K (from WSU)',0,'1','Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.0; en-US; rv:1.8.1.14) Gecko/20080404 Firefox/2.0.0.14','',0,0),(64487,11,'Jean Montare','jeanmontare@gmail.com','','81.83.4.229','2008-07-23 03:03:44','2008-07-23 10:03:44','If you buy Belgian chocolate, buy it from Belgians :D.\r\nReally nice and tasteful chocolate here : http://www.bouchard.be/',0,'1','Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; Intel Mac OS X 10.5; en-US; rv:1.9.0.1) Gecko/2008070206 Firefox/3.0.1','',0,0),(64502,424,'lonnon','lonnon.foster@gmail.com','http://nyerm.com','71.197.164.48','2008-08-17 12:33:50','2008-08-17 19:33:50','Unsurprisingly, Jott had a bit of trouble with \"bogglingly,\" truncating it to \"boggling.\" Other than that, I\'m astounded by the accuracy of the speech recognition. I\'m in a room full of fans (it\'s rather warm today) and it did a marvelous job with transcribing the post.',0,'1','Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.0; en-US; rv:1.9.0.1) Gecko/2008070208 Firefox/3.0.1','',0,2),(64506,378,'Bookmarks about Livejournal','','http://www.remmrit.com/livejournal','67.228.47.154','2008-08-30 03:46:19','2008-08-30 10:46:19','[...] - bookmarked by 4 members originally found by shmlx on 2008-08-26  Crossposting to LiveJournal  http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/07/18/crossposting-to-livejournal/ - bookmarked by 3 members originally [...]',0,'1','PHP/5.2.5','pingback',0,0),(64542,395,'Moi','moi@moi.com','','86.77.145.50','2008-09-17 14:12:45','2008-09-17 21:12:45','Hi,\r\n\r\nI just installed zsh via cydia on my iphone 3G, but how could I launch it ???\r\nNo shortcut on the springboard...\r\n\r\nThx for your help...',0,'1','Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; fr; rv:1.9.0.1) Gecko/2008070208 Firefox/3.0.1','',0,0),(64545,395,'lonnon','lonnon.foster@gmail.com','http://nyerm.com','24.17.242.36','2008-09-18 18:31:47','2008-09-19 01:31:47','zsh is a command line program only, and as such, it has no Springboard icon. Instead, you need to run it on the iPhone\'s command line. I use Mobile Terminal (available on Cydia), which is a great on-the-phone way of getting a terminal window. You can also get a command line for the iPhone by installing OpenSSH (also on Cydia), then connecting to your iPhone with a terminal program on a computer via ssh.\r\n\r\nIn the post above, I detail how I set up the @master.passwd@ file so both the @mobile@ and @root@ users on the iPhone default to using zsh instead of bash. You could also just type @zsh@ on the command line to launch it, but it\'s far more useful when set as the default shell.',0,'1','Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.0; en-US) AppleWebKit/525.13 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/0.2.149.29 Safari/525.13','',0,2),(64527,432,'James Kelly','kd7spt@hotmail.com','','67.160.150.221','2008-09-10 19:00:32','2008-09-11 02:00:32','5174.  I am not a unique little flower.',0,'1','Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.0; en-US; rv:1.9.0.1) Gecko/2008070208 Firefox/3.0.1','',0,0),(64528,432,'lonnon','lonnon.foster@gmail.com','http://nyerm.com','71.197.164.48','2008-09-10 20:12:21','2008-09-11 03:12:21','But you have joined Tyler Durden\'s Army. Congratulations!',0,'1','Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.0; en-US) AppleWebKit/525.13 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/0.2.149.29 Safari/525.13','',0,2),(64553,395,'Recent Links Tagged With \"zsh\" - JabberTags','','http://www.jabbertags.com/popular/zsh','67.228.47.154','2008-10-27 19:49:16','2008-10-28 02:49:16','[...] public links &gt;&gt; zsh   Running zsh on the iPhone Saved by Jemeela on Sun 26-10-2008   Fancy Globbing With Zsh On Linux and Unix Saved by SakuraNeji [...]',0,'1','XML-RPC for PHP 2.2.1','pingback',0,0),(64566,436,'Lewis','lewyer@gmail.com','','99.157.209.137','2008-12-05 14:19:21','2008-12-05 21:19:21','One of our coworkers used to have strange interactive properties with computers.  We determined that he was made of magnets:\r\nhttp://flickr.com/photos/snailwing/1305975210/',0,'1','Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US; rv:1.8.1.17) Gecko/20080829 Firefox/2.0.0.17','',0,0),(64600,548,'Menora','menora879@yahoo.com','http://maggiezraa29392.spaces.live.com/blog/','76.107.202.220','2009-04-22 12:18:00','2009-04-22 19:18:00','Good words.',0,'1','Mozilla/5.0 (X11; U; Linux i686; en-US; rv:1.8.1.7) Gecko/20070914 Firefox/2.0.0.7','',0,0),(64588,436,'Mike','mbell@albionresearch.com','http://www.riskythinking.com/','74.15.250.146','2009-03-15 13:16:50','2009-03-15 20:16:50','Doing this would change the file ownership / permissions, which might have been the cause of the problem...\r\n\r\n@Lewis\' magnet idea theory good, though.\r\n\r\nIncidentally, it was a bit of a shock clicking on a tribble (Palm page) link and arriving here... Took a long (internet) time to realise I was sill in the right place.',0,'1','Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.0; en-GB; rv:1.9.0.6) Gecko/2009011913 Firefox/3.0.6 (.NET CLR 3.5.30729)','',0,0),(20320,151,'Alan','apurper@norman.com','','68.50.139.12','2005-10-23 16:41:46','2005-10-23 23:41:46','This is too cool\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(22387,163,'Anon','','','68.54.76.214','2006-01-31 11:13:54','2006-01-31 18:13:54','I know this was posted a while back, BUT Alorica is one of Sony\'s outsources for their technical and customer service calls.  They are headquartered in Chino, Ca.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(22388,163,'Lonnon','lonnon.foster@gmail.com','http://blog.nyerm.com','192.94.202.44','2006-01-31 17:10:05','2006-02-01 00:10:05','Ah, so it could be Sony being underhanded, after all. Well, all the shiny has worn off this scandal, so it\'s fallen out of the public view at this point. Though Google managed to bring someone here to comment, so thanks to technology, it\'s a lot harder to bury things like this under stacks of dusty newsprint in someone\'s archive.\r\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(22391,164,'LionKimbro','lion@speakeasy.org','http://speakeasy.org/~lion/','216.254.10.130','2003-08-17 11:43:10','2003-08-17 18:43:10','Patrick Farley is awesome.\nCheck out \"The Guy I Almost Was\" as well, that\'s a favorite of mine.\nActually, check out everything. After all: Patrick Farley is awesome.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(22392,164,'Lonnon','lonnon.foster@gmail.com','http://blog.nyerm.com','207.46.228.16','2003-08-18 14:22:53','2003-08-18 21:22:53','Yes, I\'m enjoying everything on the Electric Sheep site. I\'m particularly fond of Delta Thrives, but all of it - Apocamon, The Jain\'s Death, Chrysalis Colossus - is excellent work. I just wish I\'d discovered Farley years ago.\r\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(22618,168,'','','','210.50.108.29','2003-08-15 17:19:05','2003-08-16 00:19:05','Fair and Balanced Fair and Balanced\nFair and Balanced Fair and Balanced\nFair and Balanced Fair and Balanced\nFair and Balanced Fair and Balanced\nFair and Balanced Fair and Balanced\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(22619,168,'Kris','pupcia@hotmail.com','','210.50.108.29','2003-08-15 17:20:53','2003-08-16 00:20:53','Fair and Balanced Fair and Balanced\nFair and Balanced Fair and Balanced\nFair and Balanced Fair and Balanced\nFair and Balanced Fair and Balanced\nFair and Balanced Fair and Balanced\nSorry guys, had to do it.\nKris\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(23810,177,'Jeanette Eddy','be359@scn.org','','66.90.244.243','2003-08-26 21:03:18','2003-08-27 04:03:18','Congratulations! I\'d come in and shop, but, well, I\'m living in Austin for now *wry*\nHugs to you both!\nJeanette\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(23811,177,'Drew Brown','morlith@rocketmail.com','','63.72.148.194','2003-08-27 11:15:34','2003-08-27 18:15:34','I find it amusing that I Googled for \"The Teacup\" and \"Elisabeth Knottingham\" and I found your website. Go figure! *grin*\n\nSo COOL that she had the article done! Wow! :)\n\nThe website looks smashing! Rock on!\n\nHope all is going well for you guys!\n\nCheers,\n\nDrew\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(24067,179,'Ubiquitous Gaze','','http://akira.arts.kuleuven.ac.be/hc/doos/open_code-hotkeys.html','134.58.253.115','2003-09-07 13:07:20','2003-09-07 20:07:20','<strong>Hotkeys</strong>\n\nNice little program to try out on a Sunday afternoon: XKeymacs is a keyboard utility that enables the use of...\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(24752,184,'LionKimbro','lion@speakeasy.org','http://speakeasy.org/~lion/','216.254.10.130','2003-09-04 12:47:56','2003-09-04 19:47:56','My friends and I have always envisioned \"Open Actors\".\n\nThese would be imaginary characters that could take place in various games and stories. There would be standard art in a variety of formats depicting the characters. Their personality and abilities would be written up, along with samples of how the characters talk. Rosters will tell what they did in what worlds.\n\nThe licensing is the tricky part- how do you create a license for such a character? What kind of IP is that?\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(24753,184,'Gundy','','http://www.craiggunderson.com','12.161.140.2','2004-01-21 10:57:23','2004-01-21 17:57:23','This same idea occurred to me while reading the<a href=\"http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/11.11/opensource.html\" rel=\"nofollow\"> Linus Torvalds/Open Source issue of WIRED</a>.  As usual someone beat me to it.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(25103,185,'Drew','morlith@rocketmail.com','','63.72.148.194','2003-09-15 10:36:01','2003-09-15 17:36:01','Sounds like my office. They\'ve been redoing the carpets, elevators, and other things to our building for most of this year.\n\nThis morning (around 7:30am) I hit the \"Print\" button so I could give a hard copy of a document ot my boss. The workers downstairs had perfect timing to start using an electric sander right as my printer started up. The ensuing \"BRRRRROOOWWWRRRRTTT!!!\" noise that came from directly *below* my printer gave me a minor heart attack. Hopefully, I\'ll never hear a real printer make that kind of noise. Ye Gods!\n\nThe real pisser about having interior work done on the floor beneath you is that it sounds like the floor is being cut out from underneath you a la old school Warner Brothers Cartoons with a handsaw. Especially when the floor vibrates! Gah!\n\nI\'ve heard that a sticky substance like chewing gum makes heavy machinery live up to it\'s quiet name. You might want to give that a shot if you\'re in a vindictive mood. ;P\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(26048,191,'LionKimbro','lion@speakeasy.org','http://speakeasy.org/~lion/','216.254.10.130','2003-09-20 02:37:48','2003-09-20 09:37:48','It\'s called \"bunraku\" in Japanese, I think. {:)}=\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(26049,191,'Lonnon','lonnon.foster@gmail.com','http://blog.nyerm.com','207.46.228.16','2003-09-24 09:43:04','2003-09-24 16:43:04','Thanks; I\'d forgotten what the performance art with all the black-clad stage ninja was called. I\'ve seen traditional bunraku performed before, but I\'d never seen it applied to such a modern topic (and with such modern SFX sensibilities).\r\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(29938,216,'Henry Todd','','','82.69.86.92','2005-11-26 14:42:10','2005-11-26 21:42:10','You can achieve the same effect with vanilla Textile by putting a space before your &lt;blockquote&gt; tag. For instance:\n\n&nbsp;&lt;blockquote&gt;\n\nThis is the first paragraph.\n\nThis is the second paragraph.\n\n&nbsp;&lt;/blockquote&gt;\n\nThis also has the advantage of letting you use the \"cite\" attribute.\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(31089,225,'collision detection','','http://www.collisiondetection.net/mt/archives/000594.html','209.68.1.153','2003-11-17 20:43:40','2003-11-18 03:43:40','<strong>Corporate logo trends</strong>\n\nGraphic Design:usa has assembled a list of recent trends in corporate logo design. What\'s particularly interesting is how they link the trends to developments in printing and design technologies. For example, one of the trends they note is \"transparen...\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(31621,226,'Derek SMith','Olympus9595@yahoo.com','','24.145.213.203','2004-01-22 14:36:12','2004-01-22 21:36:12','ah ha\n