d7ad4-d4c0-4cb4-a640-c9c37fe0b2ea.jpeg\"><img src=\"http://blog.nyerm.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/07/p-640-480-732d7ad4-d4c0-4cb4-a640-c9c37fe0b2ea.jpeg\" alt=\"photo\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-364\" /></a></p>','Finally moblogging',0,'','inherit','open','open','','389-revision','','','2008-07-22 17:12:30','2008-07-23 00:12:30','',389,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/07/22/389-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(391,2,'2008-07-22 17:13:35','2008-07-23 00:13:35','WordPress for iPhone is finally out, which gives me the opportunity to post random stuff from wherever I\'m standing, assuming I\'m standing within range of AT&T\'s wireless system.\n\nThis is the kind of thing I\'ve wanted for years, and though there have been ways to do this for some time now, they\'ve all been too clunky, expensive, or both for me to stay interested in them too long.\n\nI can even include pictures right from the phone, which might never get old:\n<p><a href=\"http://blog.nyerm.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/07/p-640-480-732d7ad4-d4c0-4cb4-a640-c9c37fe0b2ea.jpeg\"><img src=\"http://blog.nyerm.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/07/p-640-480-732d7ad4-d4c0-4cb4-a640-c9c37fe0b2ea.jpeg\" alt=\"photo\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-364\" /></a></p>','Finally moblogging',0,'','inherit','open','open','','389-revision-2','','','2008-07-22 17:13:35','2008-07-23 00:13:35','',389,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/07/22/389-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(393,2,'2008-08-06 12:27:39','2008-08-06 19:27:39','Adobe has staunchly refused, through several versions of Illustrator, to make it easy to produce multi-page PDF documents from Illustrator. It\'s understandable that they would prefer people to use Adobe Acrobat or InDesign for this purpose, and it may be argued that those are much better tools for the job. However, when the only tool you have is Illustrator, it\'s not nearly that simple.\n\nThis is a topic that\'s been covered elsewhere [need link], but never with all the pieces in one place where I can easily find them. Small wonder, then, that I\'ve only recently been able to get this working. These simple instructions work great for most Illustrator files, but I recently needed to make some brochures that have bleeds. With regular printer drivers (at least on a Mac; mileage may vary on Windows), Illustrator insists on trimming the edges of a multi-page PDF to fit within the printable area allowed by the printer. This isn\'t so hot when the margins include artwork that should become part of the finished PDF. \n\nHere is what I\'ve done to make this all work.\n\nh3. Preparation\n\nUnless','Multiple page PDF from Illustrator',0,'','inherit','open','open','','392-revision','','','2008-08-06 12:27:39','2008-08-06 19:27:39','',392,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/06/392-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(394,2,'2008-08-06 12:37:56','2008-08-06 19:37:56','Adobe has staunchly refused, through several versions of Illustrator, to make it easy to produce multi-page PDF documents from Illustrator. It\'s understandable that they would prefer people to use Adobe Acrobat or InDesign for this purpose, and it may be argued that those are much better tools for the job. However, when the only tool you have is Illustrator, it\'s not nearly that simple.\r\n\r\nThis is a topic that\'s been covered elsewhere [need link], but never with all the pieces in one place where I can easily find them. Small wonder, then, that I\'ve only recently been able to get this working. These simple instructions work great for most Illustrator files, but I recently needed to make some brochures that have bleeds. With regular printer drivers (at least on a Mac; mileage may vary on Windows), Illustrator insists on trimming the edges of a multi-page PDF to fit within the printable area allowed by the printer. This isn\'t so hot when the margins include artwork that should become part of the finished PDF. \r\n\r\nHere is what I\'ve done to make this all work.\r\n\r\nh3. Preparation\r\n\r\nUnless','Multiple page PDF from Illustrator',0,'','inherit','open','open','','392-revision-2','','','2008-08-06 12:37:56','2008-08-06 19:37:56','',392,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/06/392-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(395,2,'2008-08-10 12:44:03','2008-08-10 19:44:03','I jailbroke my iPhone 3G as soon as the \"iPhone Dev Team\":http://blog.iphone-dev.org had posted their tool to do so, and ever since, I\'ve been screwing about with the command line. There\'s something deeply appealing to my inner nerd about having Unix on my phone, and recreational command line hacking is more fun for me than many of the games available for iPhone.\r\n\r\nThe one thing missing on my journey to mobile nerdvana was \"zsh\":http://www.zsh.org, my favorite shell. Cydia had a zsh package available as soon as Pwnage Tool 2.0 came out, and I promptly installed it. Unfortunately, though I was able to run zsh from the command line, I couldn\'t figure out how to set it as the default login shell.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nWell, a bit of googling later, and I found out that on the iPhone (and possibly Mac OS X, whence iPhone derives much of its unixy goodness) editing @/etc/passwd@ won\'t do the trick. In fact, there\'s a big fat comment at the head of @/etc/passwd@ that informs you that editing it won\'t be particularly useful:\r\n\r\n<textarea readonly=\"readonly\" wrap=\"off\" style=\"width: 100%; font-family: Monaco, \'Courier New\', Courier, monospace; font-size: 85%;\">\r\n # Note that this file is not consulted for login.\r\n # It only exisits for compatability with 4.3BSD utilities.</textarea>\r\n\r\nHow then to set up default shells? Edit @/etc/master.passwd@, of course. iPhone uses this file as its authoritative user database, and changes to the login shell in this file work quite well. Change @/bin/sh@ to @/bin/zsh@ at the ends of the root and mobile lines, and you\'re good to go. Here\'s /etc/master.passwd after I\'ve modified it for zsh goodness:\r\n\r\n<textarea rows=\"13\" readonly=\"readonly\" wrap=\"off\" style=\"width: 100%; font-family: Monaco, \'Courier New\', Courier, monospace; font-size: 85%;\">\r\n ##\r\n # User Database\r\n #\r\n # This file is the authoritative user database.\r\n ##\r\n nobody:*:-2:-2::0:0:Unprivileged User:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\r\n root:rootpassword:0:0::0:0:System Administrator:/var/root:/bin/zsh\r\n mobile:password:501:501::0:0:Mobile User:/var/mobile:/bin/zsh\r\n daemon:*:1:1::0:0:System Services:/var/root:/usr/bin/false\r\n _securityd:*:64:64::0:0:securityd:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\r\n _mdnsresponder:*:65:65::0:0:mDNSResponder:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\r\n _sshd:*:75:75::0:0:sshd Privilege separation:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\r\n _unknown:*:99:99::0:0:Unknown User:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false</textarea>\r\n\r\nNote that you must be logged on as root to edit @/etc/master.passwd@.','Running zsh on the iPhone',0,'','publish','open','open','','running-zsh-on-the-iphone','','','2008-08-19 14:46:12','2008-08-19 21:46:12','',0,'http://blog.nyerm.com/?p=395',0,'post','',3),(396,2,'2008-08-10 11:54:47','2008-08-10 18:54:47','I jailbroke my iPhone 3G as soon as the \"iPhone Dev Team\":http://blog.iphone-dev.org had posted their tool to do so, and ever since, I\'ve been screwing about with the command line. There\'s something deeply appealing to my inner nerd about having Unix on my phone, and recreational command line hacking is more fun for me than many of the games available for iPhone.\n\nThe one thing missing on my journey to mobile nerdvana was \"zsh\":http://www.zsh.org, my favorite shell. Cydia had a zsh package available as soon as Pwnage Tool 2.0 came out, and I promptly installed it. Unfortuanately, though I was able to run zsh from the command line, I couldn\'t figure out how to set it as the default login shell.\n\n<!--more-->\n\nWell, a bit of googling later, and I found out that on the iPhone (and possibly Mac OS X, whence iPhone derives much of its unixy goodness) editing /etc/passwd won\'t do the trick. In fact, there\'s a big fat comment at the head of /etc/passwd that informs you that editing it won\'t be particularly useful:\n\n<code>\n# Note that this file is not consulted for login.\n# It only exisits for compatability with 4.3BSD utilities.\n</code>\n\nHow then to set up default shells? Edit /etc/master.passwd, of course. iPhone uses this file as its authoritative user database, and changes to the login shell in this file work quite well. Here\'s /etc/master.passwd after I\'ve modified it for zsh goodness:\n\n<code>\n##\n# User Database\n#\n# This file is the authoritative user database.\n##\nnobody:*:-2:-2::0:0:Unprivileged User:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\nroot:rootpassword:0:0::0:0:System Administrator:/var/root:<span style=\"color: green;\">/bin/zsh</span>\nmobile:password:501:501::0:0:Mobile User:/var/mobile:<span style=\"color: green;\">/bin/zsh</span>\ndaemon:*:1:1::0:0:System Services:/var/root:/usr/bin/false\n_securityd:*:64:64::0:0:securityd:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n_mdnsresponder:*:65:65::0:0:mDNSResponder:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n_sshd:*:75:75::0:0:sshd Privilege separation:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n_unknown:*:99:99::0:0:Unknown User:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n</code>\n','Running zsh on the iPhone',0,'','inherit','open','open','','395-revision','','','2008-08-10 11:54:47','2008-08-10 18:54:47','',395,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/10/395-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(397,2,'2008-08-10 11:58:35','2008-08-10 18:58:35','I jailbroke my iPhone 3G as soon as the \"iPhone Dev Team\":http://blog.iphone-dev.org had posted their tool to do so, and ever since, I\'ve been screwing about with the command line. There\'s something deeply appealing to my inner nerd about having Unix on my phone, and recreational command line hacking is more fun for me than many of the games available for iPhone.\n\nThe one thing missing on my journey to mobile nerdvana was \"zsh\":http://www.zsh.org, my favorite shell. Cydia had a zsh package available as soon as Pwnage Tool 2.0 came out, and I promptly installed it. Unfortuanately, though I was able to run zsh from the command line, I couldn\'t figure out how to set it as the default login shell.\n\n<!--more-->\n\nWell, a bit of googling later, and I found out that on the iPhone (and possibly Mac OS X, whence iPhone derives much of its unixy goodness) editing /etc/passwd won\'t do the trick. In fact, there\'s a big fat comment at the head of /etc/passwd that informs you that editing it won\'t be particularly useful:\n\n<div class=\"codesample\" style=\">\n# Note that this file is not consulted for login.\n# It only exisits for compatability with 4.3BSD utilities.\n</code>\n\nHow then to set up default shells? Edit /etc/master.passwd, of course. iPhone uses this file as its authoritative user database, and changes to the login shell in this file work quite well. Here\'s /etc/master.passwd after I\'ve modified it for zsh goodness:\n\n<code>\n##\n# User Database\n#\n# This file is the authoritative user database.\n##\nnobody:*:-2:-2::0:0:Unprivileged User:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\nroot:rootpassword:0:0::0:0:System Administrator:/var/root:<span style=\"color: green;\">/bin/zsh</span>\nmobile:password:501:501::0:0:Mobile User:/var/mobile:<span style=\"color: green;\">/bin/zsh</span>\ndaemon:*:1:1::0:0:System Services:/var/root:/usr/bin/false\n_securityd:*:64:64::0:0:securityd:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n_mdnsresponder:*:65:65::0:0:mDNSResponder:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n_sshd:*:75:75::0:0:sshd Privilege separation:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n_unknown:*:99:99::0:0:Unknown User:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n</code>\n\nNote that you must be logged on as root to edit /etc/master.passwd.','Running zsh on the iPhone',0,'','inherit','open','open','','395-revision-2','','','2008-08-10 11:58:35','2008-08-10 18:58:35','',395,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/10/395-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(400,2,'2008-08-10 12:01:31','2008-08-10 19:01:31','I jailbroke my iPhon