\"zsh\":http://www.zsh.org, my favorite shell. Cydia had a zsh package available as soon as Pwnage Tool 2.0 came out, and I promptly installed it. Unfortuanately, though I was able to run zsh from the command line, I couldn\'t figure out how to set it as the default login shell.\n\n<!--more-->\n\nWell, a bit of googling later, and I found out that on the iPhone (and possibly Mac OS X, whence iPhone derives much of its unixy goodness) editing /etc/passwd won\'t do the trick. In fact, there\'s a big fat comment at the head of /etc/passwd that informs you that editing it won\'t be particularly useful:\n\n<textarea readonly=\"readonly\" wrap=\"off\" style=\"width: 100%; font-family: Monaco, \'Courier New\', Courier, monospace; font-size: 85%;\">\n # Note that this file is not consulted for login.\n # It only exisits for compatability with 4.3BSD utilities.</textarea>\n\nHow then to set up default shells? Edit /etc/master.passwd, of course. iPhone uses this file as its authoritative user database, and changes to the login shell in this file work quite well. Here\'s /etc/master.passwd after I\'ve modified it for zsh goodness:\n\n<textarea readonly=\"readonly\" wrap=\"off\" style=\"width: 100%; font-family: Monaco, \'Courier New\', Courier, monospace; font-size: 85%;\">\n ##\n # User Database\n #\n # This file is the authoritative user database.\n ##\n nobody:*:-2:-2::0:0:Unprivileged User:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n root:rootpassword:0:0::0:0:System Administrator:/var/root:/bin/zsh\n mobile:password:501:501::0:0:Mobile User:/var/mobile:<span style=\"color: green;\">/bin/zsh</span>\n daemon:*:1:1::0:0:System Services:/var/root:/usr/bin/false\n _securityd:*:64:64::0:0:securityd:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n _mdnsresponder:*:65:65::0:0:mDNSResponder:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n _sshd:*:75:75::0:0:sshd Privilege separation:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n _unknown:*:99:99::0:0:Unknown User:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false</textarea>\n\nNote that you must be logged on as root to edit /etc/master.passwd.','Running zsh on the iPhone',0,'','inherit','open','open','','395-revision-19','','','2008-08-10 12:32:09','2008-08-10 19:32:09','',395,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/10/395-revision-19/',0,'revision','',0),(415,2,'2008-08-10 12:32:30','2008-08-10 19:32:30','I jailbroke my iPhone 3G as soon as the \"iPhone Dev Team\":http://blog.iphone-dev.org had posted their tool to do so, and ever since, I\'ve been screwing about with the command line. There\'s something deeply appealing to my inner nerd about having Unix on my phone, and recreational command line hacking is more fun for me than many of the games available for iPhone.\r\n\r\nThe one thing missing on my journey to mobile nerdvana was \"zsh\":http://www.zsh.org, my favorite shell. Cydia had a zsh package available as soon as Pwnage Tool 2.0 came out, and I promptly installed it. Unfortuanately, though I was able to run zsh from the command line, I couldn\'t figure out how to set it as the default login shell.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nWell, a bit of googling later, and I found out that on the iPhone (and possibly Mac OS X, whence iPhone derives much of its unixy goodness) editing /etc/passwd won\'t do the trick. In fact, there\'s a big fat comment at the head of /etc/passwd that informs you that editing it won\'t be particularly useful:\r\n\r\n<textarea readonly=\"readonly\" wrap=\"off\" style=\"width: 100%; font-family: Monaco, \'Courier New\', Courier, monospace; font-size: 85%;\">\r\n # Note that this file is not consulted for login.\r\n # It only exisits for compatability with 4.3BSD utilities.</textarea>\r\n\r\nHow then to set up default shells? Edit /etc/master.passwd, of course. iPhone uses this file as its authoritative user database, and changes to the login shell in this file work quite well. Here\'s /etc/master.passwd after I\'ve modified it for zsh goodness:\r\n\r\n<textarea readonly=\"readonly\" wrap=\"off\" style=\"width: 100%; font-family: Monaco, \'Courier New\', Courier, monospace; font-size: 85%;\">\r\n ##\r\n # User Database\r\n #\r\n # This file is the authoritative user database.\r\n ##\r\n nobody:*:-2:-2::0:0:Unprivileged User:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\r\n root:rootpassword:0:0::0:0:System Administrator:/var/root:/bin/zsh\r\n mobile:password:501:501::0:0:Mobile User:/var/mobile:/bin/zsh\r\n daemon:*:1:1::0:0:System Services:/var/root:/usr/bin/false\r\n _securityd:*:64:64::0:0:securityd:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\r\n _mdnsresponder:*:65:65::0:0:mDNSResponder:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\r\n _sshd:*:75:75::0:0:sshd Privilege separation:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\r\n _unknown:*:99:99::0:0:Unknown User:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false</textarea>\r\n\r\nNote that you must be logged on as root to edit /etc/master.passwd.','Running zsh on the iPhone',0,'','inherit','open','open','','395-revision-20','','','2008-08-10 12:32:30','2008-08-10 19:32:30','',395,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/10/395-revision-20/',0,'revision','',0),(416,2,'2008-08-10 12:37:22','2008-08-10 19:37:22','I jailbroke my iPhone 3G as soon as the \"iPhone Dev Team\":http://blog.iphone-dev.org had posted their tool to do so, and ever since, I\'ve been screwing about with the command line. There\'s something deeply appealing to my inner nerd about having Unix on my phone, and recreational command line hacking is more fun for me than many of the games available for iPhone.\n\nThe one thing missing on my journey to mobile nerdvana was \"zsh\":http://www.zsh.org, my favorite shell. Cydia had a zsh package available as soon as Pwnage Tool 2.0 came out, and I promptly installed it. Unfortuanately, though I was able to run zsh from the command line, I couldn\'t figure out how to set it as the default login shell.\n\n<!--more-->\n\nWell, a bit of googling later, and I found out that on the iPhone (and possibly Mac OS X, whence iPhone derives much of its unixy goodness) editing /etc/passwd won\'t do the trick. In fact, there\'s a big fat comment at the head of /etc/passwd that informs you that editing it won\'t be particularly useful:\n\n<textarea readonly=\"readonly\" wrap=\"off\" style=\"width: 100%; font-family: Monaco, \'Courier New\', Courier, monospace; font-size: 85%;\">\n # Note that this file is not consulted for login.\n # It only exisits for compatability with 4.3BSD utilities.</textarea>\n\nHow then to set up default shells? Edit /etc/master.passwd, of course. iPhone uses this file as its authoritative user database, and changes to the login shell in this file work quite well. Change @/bin/sh@ to @/bin/zsh@ at the end Here\'s /etc/master.passwd after I\'ve modified it for zsh goodness:\n\n<textarea rows=\"13\" readonly=\"readonly\" wrap=\"off\" style=\"width: 100%; font-family: Monaco, \'Courier New\', Courier, monospace; font-size: 85%;\">\n ##\n # User Database\n #\n # This file is the authoritative user database.\n ##\n nobody:*:-2:-2::0:0:Unprivileged User:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n root:rootpassword:0:0::0:0:System Administrator:/var/root:/bin/zsh\n mobile:password:501:501::0:0:Mobile User:/var/mobile:/bin/zsh\n daemon:*:1:1::0:0:System Services:/var/root:/usr/bin/false\n _securityd:*:64:64::0:0:securityd:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n _mdnsresponder:*:65:65::0:0:mDNSResponder:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n _sshd:*:75:75::0:0:sshd Privilege separation:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n _unknown:*:99:99::0:0:Unknown User:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false</textarea>\n\nNote that you must be logged on as root to edit /etc/master.passwd.','Running zsh on the iPhone',0,'','inherit','open','open','','395-revision-21','','','2008-08-10 12:37:22','2008-08-10 19:37:22','',395,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/10/395-revision-21/',0,'revision','',0),(417,2,'2008-08-10 12:40:45','2008-08-10 19:40:45','I jailbroke my iPhone 3G as soon as the \"iPhone Dev Team\":http://blog.iphone-dev.org had posted their tool to do so, and ever since, I\'ve been screwing about with the command line. There\'s something deeply appealing to my inner nerd about having Unix on my phone, and recreational command line hacking is more fun for me than many of the games available for iPhone.\n\nThe one thing missing on my journey to mobile nerdvana was \"zsh\":http://www.zsh.org, my favorite shell. Cydia had a zsh package available as soon as Pwnage Tool 2.0 came out, and I promptly installed it. Unfortuanately, though I was able to run zsh from the command line, I couldn\'t figure out how to set it as the default login shell.\n\n<!--more-->\n\nWell, a bit of googling later, and I found out that on the iPhone (and possibly Mac OS X, whence iPhone derives much of its unixy goodness) editing @/etc/passwd@ won\'t do the trick. In fact, there\'s a big fat comment at the head of @/etc/passwd@ that informs you that editing it won\'t be particularly useful:\n\n<textarea readonly=\"readonly\" wrap=\"off\" style=\"width: 100%; font-family: Monaco, \'Courier New\', Courier, monospace; font-size: 85%;\">\n # Note that this file is not consulted for login.\n # It only exisits for compatability with 4.3BSD utilities.</textarea>\n\nHow then to set up default shells? Edit /etc/master.passwd, of course. iPhone uses this file as its authoritative user database, and changes to the login shell in this file work quite well. Change @/bin/sh@ to @/bin/zsh@ at the ends of the root and mobile lines, and you\'re good to go. Here\'s /etc/master.passwd after I\'ve modified it for zsh goodness:\n\n<textarea rows=\"13\" readonly=\"readonly\" wrap=\"off\" style=\"width: 100%; font-family: Monaco, \'Courier New\', Courier, monospace; font-size: 85%;\">\n ##\n # User Database\n #\n # This file is the authoritative user database.\n ##\n nobody:*:-2:-2::0:0:Unprivileged User:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n root:rootpassword:0:0::0:0:System Administrator:/var/root:/bin/zsh\n mobile:password:501:501::0:0:Mobile User:/var/mobile:/bin/zsh\n daemon:*:1:1::0:0:System Services:/var/root:/usr/bin/false\n _securityd:*:64:64::0:0:securityd:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n _mdnsresponder:*:65:65::0:0:mDNSResponder:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n _sshd:*:75:75::0:0:sshd Privilege separation:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\n _unknown:*:99:99::0:0:Unknown User:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false</textarea>\n\nNote that you must be logged on as root to edit /etc/master.passwd.','Running zsh on the iPhone',0,'','inherit','open','open','','395-revision-22','','','2008-08-10 12:40:45','2008-08-10 19:40:45','',395,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/10/395-revision-22/',0,'revision','',0),(418,2,'2008-08-10 12:41:10','2008-08-10 19:41:10','I jailbroke my iPhone 3G as soon as the \"iPhone Dev Team\":http://blog.iphone-dev.org had posted their tool to do so, and ever since, I\'ve been screwing about with the command line. There\'s something deeply appealing to my inner nerd about having Unix on my phone, and recreational command line hacking is more fun for me than many of the games available for iPhone.\r\n\r\nThe one thing missing on my journey to mobile nerdvana was \"zsh\":http://www.zsh.org, my favorite shell. Cydia had a zsh package available as soon as Pwnage Tool 2.0 came out, and I promptly installed it. Unfortuanately, though I was able to run zsh from the command line, I couldn\'t figure out how to set it as the default login shell.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nWell, a bit of googling later, and I found out that on the iPhone (and possibly Mac OS X, whence iPhone derives much of its unixy goodness) editing @/etc/passwd@ won\'t do the trick. In fact, there\'s a big fat comment at the head of @/etc/passwd@ that informs you that editing it won\'t be particularly useful:\r\n\r\n<textarea readonly=\"readonly\" wrap=\"off\" style=\"width: 100%; font-family: Monaco, \'Courier New\', Courier, monospace; font-size: 85%;\">\r\n # Note that this file is not consulted for login.\r\n # It only exisits for compatability with 4.3BSD utilities.</textarea>\r\n\r\nHow then to set up default shells? Edit @/etc/master.passwd@, of course. iPhone uses this file as its authoritative user database, and changes to the login shell in this file work quite well. Change @/bin/sh@ to @/bin/zsh@ at the ends of the root and mobile lines, and you\'re good to go. Here\'s /etc/master.passwd after I\'ve modified it for zsh goodness:\r\n\r\n<textarea rows=\"13\" readonly=\"readonly\" wrap=\"off\" style=\"width: 100%; font-family: Monaco, \'Courier New\', Courier, monospace; font-size: 85%;\">\r\n ##\r\n # User Database\r\n #\r\n # This file is the authoritative user database.\r\n ##\r\n nobody:*:-2:-2::0:0:Unprivileged User:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\r\n root:rootpassword:0:0::0:0:System Administrator:/var/root:/bin/zsh\r\n mobile:password:501:501::0:0:Mobile User:/var/mobile:/bin/zsh\r\n daemon:*:1:1::0:0:System Services:/var/root:/usr/bin/false\r\n _securityd:*:64:64::0:0:securityd:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\r\n _mdnsresponder:*:65:65::0:0:mDNSResponder:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\r\n _sshd:*:75:75::0:0:sshd Privilege separation:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\r\n _unknown:*:99:99::0:0:Unknown User:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false</textarea>\r\n\r\nNote that you must be logged on as root to edit @/etc/master.passwd@.','Running zsh on the iPhone',0,'','inherit','open','open','','395-revision-23','','','2008-08-10 12:41:10','2008-08-10 19:41:10','',395,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/10/395-revision-23/',0,'revision','',0),(419,2,'2008-08-10 13:41:44','2008-08-10 20:41:44','Adobe has staunchly refused, through several versions of Illustrator, to make it easy to produce multi-page PDF documents from Illustrator. It\'s understandable that they would prefer people to use Adobe Acrobat or InDesign for this purpose, and it may be argued that those are much better tools for the job. However, when the only tool you have is Illustrator, it\'s not nearly that simple.\n\nThis is a topic that\'s been covered \"elsewhere\":http://www.lifeclever.com/how-to-create-multi-page-pdfs-in-illustrator-cs2/, but never with all the pieces in one place where I can easily find them. Small wonder, then, that I\'ve only recently been able to get this working. These simple instructions work great for most Illustrator files, but I recently needed to make some brochures that have bleeds. With regular printer drivers (at least on a Mac; mileage may vary on Windows), Illustrator insists on trimming the edges of a multi-page PDF to fit within the printable area allowed by the printer. This isn\'t so hot when the margins include artwork that should become part of the finished PDF.\n\n<!--more-->\n\nHere\'s how I\'ve made this all work.\n\nh3. Install Adobe \n\nUnless you\'ve already got a driver for a printer that prints all the way to the edges of the paper, you\'ll need a driver that does. This was my primary stumbling block; the Lexpro I normally print to at work is a pretty basic black and white laser printer, and it doesn\'t print to the edges.\n\nFortunately, Adobe has a ','Multiple page PDF from Illustrator',0,'','inherit','open','open','','392-revision-3','','','2008-08-10 13:41:44','2008-08-10 20:41:44','',392,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/10/392-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(420,2,'2008-08-10 13:43:09','2008-08-10 20:43:09','Adobe has staunchly refused, through several versions of Illustrator, to make it easy to produce multi-page PDF documents from Illustrator. It\'s understandable that they would prefer people to use Adobe Acrobat or InDesign for this purpose, and it may be argued that those are much better tools for the job. However, when the only tool you have is Illustrator, it\'s not nearly that simple.\r\n\r\nThis is a topic that\'s been covered \"elsewhere\":http://www.lifeclever.com/how-to-create-multi-page-pdfs-in-illustrator-cs2/, but never with all the pieces in one place where I can easily find them. Small wonder, then, that I\'ve only recently been able to get this working. These simple instructions work great for most Illustrator files, but I recently needed to make some brochures that have bleeds. With regular printer drivers (at least on a Mac; mileage may vary on Windows), Illustrator insists on trimming the edges of a multi-page PDF to fit within the printable area allowed by the printer. This isn\'t so hot when the margins include artwork that should become part of the finished PDF.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nHere\'s how I\'ve made this all work.\r\n\r\nh3. Install Adobe \r\n\r\nUnless you\'ve already got a driver for a printer that prints all the way to the edges of the paper, you\'ll need a driver that does. This was my primary stumbling block; the Lexpro I normally print to at work is a pretty basic black and white laser printer, and it doesn\'t print to the edges.\r\n\r\nFortunately, Adobe has a generic PostScript driver available.','Multiple page PDF from Illustrator',0,'','inherit','open','open','','392-revision-4','','','2008-08-10 13:43:09','2008-08-10 20:43:09','',392,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/10/392-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(421,2,'2008-08-10 13:50:14','2008-08-10 20:50:14','Adobe has staunchly refused, through several versions of Illustrator, to make it easy to produce multi-page PDF documents from Illustrator. It\'s understandable that they would prefer people to use Adobe Acrobat or InDesign for this purpose, and it may be argued that those are much better tools for the job. However, when the only tool you have is Illustrator, it\'s not nearly that simple.\n\nThis is a topic that\'s been covered \"elsewhere\":http://www.lifeclever.com/how-to-create-multi-page-pdfs-in-illustrator-cs2/, but never with all the pieces in one place where I can easily find them. Small wonder, then, that I\'ve only recently been able to get this working. These simple instructions work great for most Illustrator files, but I recently needed to make some brochures that have bleeds. With most printer drivers, Illustrator insists on trimming the edges of a multi-page PDF to fit within the printable area allowed by the printer. This isn\'t so hot when the margins include artwork that should become part of the finished PDF.\n\n<!--more-->\n\nHere\'s how I\'ve made this all work.\n\nh3. Install Adobe generic PostScript driver\n\nUnless you\'ve already got a driver for a printer that prints all the way to the edges of the paper, you\'ll need a driver that does. This was my primary stumbling block; the Lexpro I normally print to at work is a pretty basic black and white laser printer, and it doesn\'t print to the edges.\n\nFortunately, Adobe has a generic PostScript driver available.','Multiple page PDF from Illustrator',0,'','inherit','open','open','','392-revision-5','','','2008-08-10 13:50:14','2008-08-10 20:50:14','',392,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/10/392-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(422,2,'2008-08-10 14:03:25','2008-08-10 21:03:25','Adobe has staunchly refused, through several versions of Illustrator, to make it easy to produce multi-page PDF documents from Illustrator. It\'s understandable that they would prefer people to use Adobe Acrobat or InDesign for this purpose, and it may be argued that those are much better tools for the job. However, when the only tool you have is Illustrator, it\'s not nearly that simple.\n\nThis is a topic that\'s been covered \"elsewhere\":http://www.lifeclever.com/how-to-create-multi-page-pdfs-in-illustrator-cs2/, but never with all the pieces in one place where I can easily find them. Small wonder, then, that I\'ve only recently been able to get this working. These simple instructions work great for most Illustrator files, but I recently needed to make some brochures that have bleeds. With most printer drivers, Illustrator insists on trimming the edges of a multi-page PDF to fit within the printable area allowed by the printer. This isn\'t so hot when the margins include artwork that should become part of the finished PDF.\n\n<!--more-->\n\nHere\'s how I\'ve made this all work.\n\nh3. Install Adobe generic PostScript driver\n\nUnless you\'ve already got a driver for a printer that prints all the way to the edges of the paper, you\'ll need a driver that does. This was my primary stumbling block; the Lexpro I normally print to at work is a pretty basic black and white laser printer, and it doesn\'t print to the edges.\n\nFortunately, Adobe has a generic PostScript driver available.\n\nhttp://www.adobe.com/support/downloads/product.jsp?product=44&platform=Windows\nIn Windows Illustrator, printer appears as Adobe PDF','Multiple page PDF from Illustrator',0,'','inherit','open','open','','392-revision-6','','','2008-08-10 14:03:25','2008-08-10 21:03:25','',392,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/10/392-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(423,2,'2008-08-12 18:44:54','2008-08-13 01:44:54','Adobe has staunchly refused, through several versions of Illustrator, to make it easy to produce multi-page PDF documents from Illustrator. It\'s understandable that they would prefer people to use Adobe Acrobat or InDesign for this purpose, and it may be argued that those are much better tools for the job. However, when the only tool you have is Illustrator, it\'s not nearly that simple.\n\nThis is a topic that\'s been covered \"elsewhere\":http://www.lifeclever.com/how-to-create-multi-page-pdfs-in-illustrator-cs2/, but never with all the pieces in one place where I can easily find them. Small wonder, then, that I\'ve only recently been able to get this working. These simple instructions work great for most Illustrator files, but I recently needed to make some brochures that have bleeds. With most printer drivers, Illustrator insists on trimming the edges of a multi-page PDF to fit within the printable area allowed by the printer. This isn\'t so hot when the margins include artwork that should become part of the finished PDF.\n\n<!--more-->\n\nHere\'s how I\'ve made this all work.\n\nh3. Install Adobe generic PostScript driver\n\nUnless you\'ve already got a driver for a printer that prints all the way to the edges of the paper, you\'ll need a driver that does. This was my primary stumbling block; the Lexpro I normally print to at work is a pretty basic black and white laser printer, and it doesn\'t print to the edges.\n\nFortunately, Adobe has a generic PostScript Printer Description (PPD) file available for download. A PPD normally describes what capabilities a PostScript printer has. The generic PPD lacks the usual printable area that restricts most printers to use only part of the page, and thus it\'s useful for generating PDF files with bleeds.\n\nThe Windows \n\nhttp://www.adobe.com/support/downloads/product.jsp?product=44&platform=Windows\nIn Windows Illustrator, printer appears as Adobe PDF\nhttp://www.adobe.com/support/downloads/detail.jsp?ftpID=204\n\n\nMac:\nhttp://www.adobe.com/support/downloads/detail.jsp?ftpID=141\nPostScript Printer Description file','Multiple page PDF from Illustrator',0,'','inherit','open','open','','392-revision-7','','','2008-08-12 18:44:54','2008-08-13 01:44:54','',392,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/12/392-revision-7/',0,'revision','',0),(424,2,'2008-08-17 12:24:45','2008-08-17 19:24:45','Jott is a mind boggling cool technology. I\'m currently posting to my blog by calling a phone number and having it transcribe everything and stick it into a blog post. The future is here and man it\'s really damn cool. <a href=\"http://www.jott.com/show.aspx?id=9d4068be-8611-43c9-baad-5b596666c9d1\" target=\"_blank\">listen</a>\r\n\r\nPowered by <a href=\"http://jott.com\" target=\"_blank\">Jott</a>','Jott is a mind boggling...',0,'','publish','open','open','','jott-is-a-mind-boggling','','','2008-08-17 14:56:06','2008-08-17 21:56:06','',0,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/17/jott-is-a-mind-boggling/',0,'post','',1),(425,2,'2008-08-17 12:24:45','2008-08-17 19:24:45','Jott is a mind boggling cool technology. I\'m currently posting to my blog by calling a phone number and having it transcribe everything and stick it into a blog post. The future is here and man it\'s really damn cool. <a href=\"http://www.jott.com/show.aspx?id=9d4068be-8611-43c9-baad-5b596666c9d1\" target=\"_blank\">listen</a>\n\nPowered by <a href=\"http://jott.com\" target=\"_blank\">Jott</a>','Jott is a mind boggling...',0,'','inherit','open','open','','424-revision','','','2008-08-17 12:24:45','2008-08-17 19:24:45','',424,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/17/424-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(426,2,'2008-08-10 12:44:03','2008-08-10 19:44:03','I jailbroke my iPhone 3G as soon as the \"iPhone Dev Team\":http://blog.iphone-dev.org had posted their tool to do so, and ever since, I\'ve been screwing about with the command line. There\'s something deeply appealing to my inner nerd about having Unix on my phone, and recreational command line hacking is more fun for me than many of the games available for iPhone.\r\n\r\nThe one thing missing on my journey to mobile nerdvana was \"zsh\":http://www.zsh.org, my favorite shell. Cydia had a zsh package available as soon as Pwnage Tool 2.0 came out, and I promptly installed it. Unfortuanately, though I was able to run zsh from the command line, I couldn\'t figure out how to set it as the default login shell.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nWell, a bit of googling later, and I found out that on the iPhone (and possibly Mac OS X, whence iPhone derives much of its unixy goodness) editing @/etc/passwd@ won\'t do the trick. In fact, there\'s a big fat comment at the head of @/etc/passwd@ that informs you that editing it won\'t be particularly useful:\r\n\r\n<textarea readonly=\"readonly\" wrap=\"off\" style=\"width: 100%; font-family: Monaco, \'Courier New\', Courier, monospace; font-size: 85%;\">\r\n # Note that this file is not consulted for login.\r\n # It only exisits for compatability with 4.3BSD utilities.</textarea>\r\n\r\nHow then to set up default shells? Edit @/etc/master.passwd@, of course. iPhone uses this file as its authoritative user database, and changes to the login shell in this file work quite well. Change @/bin/sh@ to @/bin/zsh@ at the ends of the root and mobile lines, and you\'re good to go. Here\'s /etc/master.passwd after I\'ve modified it for zsh goodness:\r\n\r\n<textarea rows=\"13\" readonly=\"readonly\" wrap=\"off\" style=\"width: 100%; font-family: Monaco, \'Courier New\', Courier, monospace; font-size: 85%;\">\r\n ##\r\n # User Database\r\n #\r\n # This file is the authoritative user database.\r\n ##\r\n nobody:*:-2:-2::0:0:Unprivileged User:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\r\n root:rootpassword:0:0::0:0:System Administrator:/var/root:/bin/zsh\r\n mobile:password:501:501::0:0:Mobile User:/var/mobile:/bin/zsh\r\n daemon:*:1:1::0:0:System Services:/var/root:/usr/bin/false\r\n _securityd:*:64:64::0:0:securityd:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\r\n _mdnsresponder:*:65:65::0:0:mDNSResponder:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\r\n _sshd:*:75:75::0:0:sshd Privilege separation:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false\r\n _unknown:*:99:99::0:0:Unknown User:/var/empty:/usr/bin/false</textarea>\r\n\r\nNote that you must be logged on as root to edit @/etc/master.passwd@.','Running zsh on the iPhone',0,'','inherit','open','open','','395-revision-24','','','2008-08-10 12:44:03','2008-08-10 19:44:03','',395,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/10/395-revision-24/',0,'revision','',0),(427,2,'2008-08-29 18:58:10','2008-08-30 01:58:10','Mobile Safari\'s multiple window interface is amazing, but it lacks the ability to explicitly open a link in a new window. Being a fan of tabbed browsing in desktop browsers, I find it irritating not to be able to leave the current window in place while I follow a link or two.\n\nI don\'t have a clever hack to force Safari to open a link in a new window, but I do have the next best thing: a javascript bookmarklet that opens the current page in a new window. This makes following a link in a new window possible, if a bit inelegant.\n\n<!--more-->\n\nTo install the bookmarklet:\n\n<ol>\n<li>Drag the Clone Window link below to your bookmark bar in desktop Safari. Or if you sync to Internet Explorer, right-click the link and choose Add to Favorites, then save it to the Links folder.\n\n<a href=\"javascript:void(window.open(location.href))\">Clone Window</a></li>\n<li>Now that you have the bookmarklet on your browser\'s link bar, connect your iPhone to your computer and sync bookmarks through iTunes.</li>\n</ol>\n\nTo use the bookmarklet:\n\n<ol>\n<li>In Mobile Safari, tap the bookmarks button (open book icon) at the bottom of the screen.</li>\n<li>Locate the Clone Window bookmark; it\'s in the Bookmarks Bar folder if you sync with Safari, or in the Links folder if you sync with IE.</ok>\n<li>Tap the Clone Window bookmark. Mobile Safari opens a copy of the current page in a new window. You may now follow any link on the page, secure in the knowledge that the page you started from will still be there in another window.</li>\n</ok>\n\nHappy browsing!\n \n\n','iPhone clone window bookmarklet',0,'','publish','open','open','','iphone-clone-window-bookmarklet','','','2008-08-30 03:27:16','2008-08-30 10:27:16','',0,'http://blog.nyerm.com/?p=427',0,'post','',0),(428,2,'2008-08-29 18:58:10','2008-08-30 01:58:10','Mobile Safari\'s multiple window interface is amazing, but it lacks the ability to explicitly open a link in a new window. Being a fan of tabbed browsing in desktop browsers, I find it irritating not to be able to leave the current window in place while I follow a link or two.\n\nI don\'t have a clever hack to force Safari to open a link in a new window, but I do have the next best thing: a javascript bookmarklet that opens the current page in a new window. This makes following a link in a new window possible, if a bit inelegant.\n\nTo install the bookmarklet:\n\n# Drag the Clone Window link below to your bookmark bar in desktop Safari. Or if you sync to Internet Explorer, right-click the link and choose Add to Favorites, then save it to the Links folder.\n\n<a href=\"javascript:void(window.open(location.href))\">Clone Window</a>\n\n# Now that you have the bookmarklet on your browser\'s link bar, connect your iPhone to your computer and sync bookmarks through iTunes.\n\nTo use the bookmarklet:\n\n# In Mobile Safari, tap the bookmarks button (open book icon) at the bottom of the screen.\n\n# Locate the Clone Window bookmark; it\'s in the Bookmarks Bar folder if you sync with Safari, or in the Links folder if you sync with IE.\n\n# Tap the Clone Window bookmark. Mobile Safari opens a copy of the current page in a new window. You may now follow any link on the page, secure in the knowledge that the page you started from will still be there in another window.\n\nHappy browsing!\n \n\n','iPhone clone window bookmarklet',0,'','inherit','open','open','','427-revision','','','2008-08-29 18:58:10','2008-08-30 01:58:10','',427,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/29/427-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(429,2,'2008-08-30 03:21:15','2008-08-30 10:21:15','Mobile Safari\'s multiple window interface is amazing, but it lacks the ability to explicitly open a link in a new window. Being a fan of tabbed browsing in desktop browsers, I find it irritating not to be able to leave the current window in place while I follow a link or two.\n\nI don\'t have a clever hack to force Safari to open a link in a new window, but I do have the next best thing: a javascript bookmarklet that opens the current page in a new window. This makes following a link in a new window possible, if a bit inelegant.\n\nTo install the bookmarklet:\n\n<ol>\n<li>Drag the Clone Window link below to your bookmark bar in desktop Safari. Or if you sync to Internet Explorer, right-click the link and choose Add to Favorites, then save it to the Links folder.\n\n<a href=\"javascript:void(window.open(location.href))\">Clone Window</a></li>\n<li>Now that you have the bookmarklet on your browser\'s link bar, connect your iPhone to your computer and sync bookmarks through iTunes.</li>\n</ol>\n\nTo use the bookmarklet:\n\n# In Mobile Safari, tap the bookmarks button (open book icon) at the bottom of the screen.\n# Locate the Clone Window bookmark; it\'s in the Bookmarks Bar folder if you sync with Safari, or in the Links folder if you sync with IE.\n# Tap the Clone Window bookmark. Mobile Safari opens a copy of the current page in a new window. You may now follow any link on the page, secure in the knowledge that the page you started from will still be there in another window.\n\nHappy browsing!\n \n\n','iPhone clone window bookmarklet',0,'','inherit','open','open','','427-revision-2','','','2008-08-30 03:21:15','2008-08-30 10:21:15','',427,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/30/427-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(430,2,'2008-08-30 03:25:42','2008-08-30 10:25:42','Mobile Safari\'s multiple window interface is amazing, but it lacks the ability to explicitly open a link in a new window. Being a fan of tabbed browsing in desktop browsers, I find it irritating not to be able to leave the current window in place while I follow a link or two.\n\nI don\'t have a clever hack to force Safari to open a link in a new window, but I do have the next best thing: a javascript bookmarklet that opens the current page in a new window. This makes following a link in a new window possible, if a bit inelegant.\n\n<!--more-->\n\nTo install the bookmarklet:\n\n<ol>\n<li>Drag the Clone Window link below to your bookmark bar in desktop Safari. Or if you sync to Internet Explorer, right-click the link and choose Add to Favorites, then save it to the Links folder.\n\n<a href=\"javascript:void(window.open(location.href))\">Clone Window</a></li>\n<li>Now that you have the bookmarklet on your browser\'s link bar, connect your iPhone to your computer and sync bookmarks through iTunes.</li>\n</ol>\n\nTo use the bookmarklet:\n\n<ol>\n<li>In Mobile Safari, tap the bookmarks button (open book icon) at the bottom of the screen.</li>\n<li>Locate the Clone Window bookmark; it\'s in the Bookmarks Bar folder if you sync with Safari, or in the Links folder if you sync with IE.</ok>\n<li>Tap the Clone Window bookmark. Mobile Safari opens a copy of the current page in a new window. You may now follow any link on the page, secure in the knowledge that the page you started from will still be there in another window.</li>\n</ok>\n\nHappy browsing!\n \n\n','iPhone clone window bookmarklet',0,'','inherit','open','open','','427-revision-3','','','2008-08-30 03:25:42','2008-08-30 10:25:42','',427,'http://blog.nyerm.com/2008/08/30/427-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(431,2,'2008-09-01 22:23:37','0000-00-00 00:00:00','A couple new apps showed up today in Cydia, \n\nSo far, so good, but they appear to be different versions of the same program. I\'m not certain why there are two of them up in Cydia, and both on the iSpazio repository at that. ComicViewer has \"Aug 9 2008\" on its settings screen, with a little tool icon in the lower right of the list view for opening settings. iComic has \"Aug 15 2008\" on the settings screen, and uses a text \"Settings\" button in the upper right to open the settings screen. There are other small differences between controls on the settings screens, but otherwise, the two apps seem to work in identical fashion.\n\nAs for reading comics, it works quite well. I nabbed some of the free comics available on ComicBookLover\'s sample page (http://bitcartel.com/comicbooklover/samplecomics.html) and gave them a spin. It took me a while to figure out where the hot spots on the screen are for the \"button\" mode of navigation, but figured out that tapping the lower left and lower right corners ','Trying out iComic and ComicViewer',0,'','draft','open','open','','','','','2008-09-01 22:23:37','2008-09-02 05:23:37','',0,'http://blog.nyerm.com/?p=431',0,'post','',0),(432,2,'2008-09-02 19:16:22','2008-09-03 02:16:22','One of the best bits about being me: I have a unique name.\r\n\r\n<div style=\"color: #000;\"><br /><table width=\"350\" bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\" cellpadding=\"1\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"background-color: white; text-align: center;\"><tr><td style=\"background-color: #0066B3; color: white; font: 16px/1.1 Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;\">HowManyOfMe.com</td></t